<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Bent-Over-Row">Dumbbell Bent-Over Row</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-bent-over-row" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell bent-over row</a> is an approachable alternative for those who struggle with full-bodyweight pull ups. That’s because pull ups require you to lift your entire body vertically against gravity. You need significant upper body strength and consistent practice to master them.</p>



<p>On the other hand, bent-over rows involve pulling dumbbells horizontally toward your torso (chest parallel to the ground). This allows for a more natural and free movement with less strain on the shoulders. They reduce <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4916995/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">the risk of shoulder impingement</a> by avoiding the high arm position that comes with pull ups.</p>



<p>Dumbbell rows are also highly versatile. They can be performed with a single arm and various equipment, such as bands, barbells, and kettlebells. They also allow you to adjust the weight for your fitness level and focus on your form.</p>



<p>This also makes it accessible for beginners wanting to build upper-body strength and muscle mass. They work similar muscle groups to pull ups. These include the latissimus dorsi, middle traps, and rhomboids along with the biceps and forearms.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Conditioning these muscles can help you develop the strength needed for pull ups. Additionally, it makes a great addition to any <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/back-and-bicep-workout" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">back and bicep workout.</a></p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Dumbbell Bent-Over Row" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/996059631?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Bent-Over Row Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong><strong>How To Do</strong></strong></h4>



<ol type="video" class="wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom">
<li>Stand with your feet hip-width apart.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Hold a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing each other.</li>



<li>Bend your knees slightly, and hinge forward at the hips until your torso is parallel to the ground.</li>



<li>Extend your arm fully with the dumbbells directly below your shoulders.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Inhale and brace your core.</li>



<li>Exhale as you pull the dumbbells to your waist.</li>



<li>Lower the dumbbells to the start by extending your arms.</li>



<li>Repeat for the desired sets and reps.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Tips</strong></h4>



<ul type="video" class="wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom">
<li>Keep your back straight, and core braced throughout the movement to prevent rounding.</li>



<li>Keep your elbows close to your body as you pull, and drive it behind you. Avoid flaring them out.</li>



<li>Squeeze your shoulder blade slightly back and pull with your back muscles.</li>



<li>Avoid twisting your torso as you pull, maintain a static torso throughout.</li>



<li>Control the weight as you return to the starting position.</li>



<li>Use a weight that doesn’t compromise your form.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Optimal Sets And Reps</strong></h4>



