<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Standing-Cable-Lat-Pulldown">Standing Cable Lat Pulldown</h3>



<p>Similarly to pull ups, the <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/standing-cable-lat-pulldown" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">standing cable lat pulldown</a> targets the latissimus dorsi. Additionally, it engages the rhomboids, traps, and biceps. However, pull ups use your body weight for resistance, which might take time and practice to master.&nbsp;</p>



<p>In contrast, lat pulldowns use a weighted cable machine, allowing you to adjust the amount of weight you lift. Therefore, cable lat pulldowns are a good alternative to pull ups. Along with these benefits, strengthening the latissimus dorsi can help build a V-shaped back, giving the illusion of wider shoulders and a slimmer waist.</p>



<p>Since your lats are the bridge between your upper and lower body, it has many other key functions. It plays a significant role in stabilizing the shoulders, and trunk, and contributing to a better posture.<br>If you don’t have a gym membership, don’t worry! Lat pulldowns make a great addition to your <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/back-workouts-at-home" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">back workouts at home</a>. You can mimic the cable pull with a long resistance band.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Cable Standing Lat Pulldown" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/993374078?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Standing Cable Lat Pulldown Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong><strong>How To Do</strong></strong></h4>



<ol type="video" class="wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom">
<li>Set the cable pulleys up so it&#8217;s above your head height.</li>



<li>Attach a straight bar or a wide-grip handle to it.</li>



<li>Grip the bar with both hands with an overhand grip.</li>



<li>Face the column bar, and take a big step back to create tension on the cable.</li>



<li>Extend your arms fully and hinge at your hips slightly.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Inhale as you pull the bar down towards your upper chest by bringing the elbows down and slightly out.</li>



<li>Pause at the bottom.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Exhale and extend your arms back to the start in a controlled manner.</li>



<li>Repeat for the desired reps and set.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Tips</strong></h4>



<ul type="video" class="wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom">
<li>Make sure you have a secure base, standing with your feet shoulder-width apart. This can prevent you from being off balance.</li>



<li>Maintain a strong grip on the bar throughout the exercise.</li>



<li>Squeeze your shoulder blade slightly back and down and you pull the bar.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Keep your torso static, avoid moving up and down.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Optimal Sets And Reps</strong></h4>



